00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:32.000
Scrum, Agile, paired programming.

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:35.000
None of these things sound appealing to me.

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:39.000
And when Agile first came out, I thought, "Oh, this is really interesting."

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:43.000
I find that in practice, maybe in principle it sounds cool.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:45.000
But, for me, it's all distracting.

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:47.000
It's all friction and stuff.

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:49.000
Yep.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:50.000
What are your thoughts?

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:51.000
I don't want to put words in your mouth.

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:52.000
I'm talking about myself.

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:53.000
So, how do you feel about these things?

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:54.000
No, no, no.

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:55.000
Yeah, no.

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:56.000
Yes, I agree.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:07.000
I talked recently, or I wrote recently, about how stand-ups are just productivity killers

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:10.000
for me, depending on when they happen and how they work.

00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:13.000
So, my productivity is variable.

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:19.000
I have days where I will do eight hours worth of work in four hours, and I'll do that twice.

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:22.000
So, I'll get two or three days worth of work done in a day.

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:25.000
I'll have days where I get nothing done.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:31.000
Something like a daily stand-up really plays into this idea that you are consistently productive

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:32.000
every day.

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:35.000
And if I have two or three days where I have to at stand-up say, "Yeah, I'm still working

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:39.000
on that thing that probably should have only taken an hour, but I can't make myself do

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:41.000
it," I look like a jerk.

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:42.000
I look like a bad employee.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:43.000
Right?

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:44.000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:48.000
Instead of you have to show how you failed that.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:49.000
Yeah.

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:53.000
And then that can create this self-esteem spiral of, "Oh, I'm really bad at this.

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:55.000
Everybody else is getting all this stuff done.

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:56.000
Maybe I don't belong here.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:58.000
Imposter syndrome, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah."

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:07.000
Similarly, things like two-week sprints and a lot of those rigid processes, I get why

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:08.000
they exist.

00:59:08.000 --> 00:59:11.000
I understand that they can work well in certain spaces.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:16.000
I think it's good to have deadlines on when things are going to show some meaningful progress.

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:27.000
But for the way that I work, I find that having those kind of rigid fixed deadlines creates

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:32.000
bad stress for me and doesn't always align with when my brain is like, "Yes, we're going

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.000
to crank out a ton of work."

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:41.000
I personally need a little bit more flexibility than those types of systems allow.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:42.000
Yeah.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:46.000
So it's one of those, "Maybe good for other people, but not good for me," kind of things.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:47.000
Yeah.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:50.000
Yeah, I don't know.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:51.000
And paired programming?

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:55.000
How does that fit with people's ADHD?

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:59.000
It depends.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:06.000
If I am having a problem with code and I am just absolutely stuck, paired programming

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:09.000
my way through it can be invaluable.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:14.000
Paired programming just for the sake of paired programming is a nightmare for me because

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:18.000
it makes me feel really self-conscious about what I'm doing and how quickly my brain processes

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:21.000
information and my process.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:26.000
I like paired programming with other people who need help as well, like in a mentoring

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:30.000
capacity if they're trying to work through something and they just need someone to guide

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:32.000
them, happy to do that.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:33.000
Sure.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:36.000
I feel a little more like mentoring.

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:37.000
Yeah.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:40.000
But just classic, I just generally...

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:45.000
I know some organizations are really big on, "You two are going to work on this feature

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:46.000
together."

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:47.000
Yes.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:48.000
That does not work for me.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:53.000
I've heard people who really love it.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:54.000
They find it very valuable.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:56.000
I'm not trying to take away from that.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:58.000
This is not one of those, "I think it's bad for everybody."

01:00:58.000 --> 01:00:59.000
It sucks for me.

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:02.000
I think it sucks for a lot of folks with ADHD.

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:03.000
Yeah.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:06.000
I just can't get in a flow if I'm sitting and working with somebody.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:07.000
Yeah, exactly.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:12.000
I might be having a good time, but it's really hard to reach that really high level of productivity.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:13.000
Yeah.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:16.000
Let's close this out with a bit of a joke, okay?

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:18.000
Maybe something practical.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:25.000
You talked about the time blindness, estimating is hard, Agile is all about estimates and

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:26.000
stuff.

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:31.000
I saw this pretty cool article I talked about on another podcast, Python Bytes.

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:34.000
Basically, hard to swallow a truth they don't tell you about software engineering, but they

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:39.000
have a really great cartoon in here that says, from monkeyuser.com, is actually where it's

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:40.000
originally from.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:43.000
It's trying to reimagine how you might estimate.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:50.000
It says, "For better estimates, instead of points or hours, we switched to measuring

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:51.000
story points too.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:57.000
How many duck-sized horses you're willing to fight rather than implementing this task?"

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:03.000
There's no duck you would fight for because it's so easy, or you'd take on a whole cavalry

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:05.000
of small duck horses?

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:06.000
I don't know.

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:07.000
What do you think?

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:16.000
I know it's a joke, but I find the stake in the ground comparisons for estimates useful.

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:21.000
I still don't think I'll always get to an accurate place, but if I say, "I don't know

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:24.000
how long something's going to take," and someone says, "Well, do you think it would take 20

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:25.000
hours?"

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:30.000
That gives me an instant grounding of, "Oh, that feels too high, that feels too low,"

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:31.000
or just right.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:34.000
It's still, in my opinion, a bit of a wild guess.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:43.000
Once you start doing the work, you will expose things like unknowns that make, "Oh, we thought

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:46.000
this, but based on this other thing, it's going to take longer, or it's going to take

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:49.000
way less, or it's going to take about what we thought."

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:54.000
Having some sort of grounding, whether it's a number of hours or horse-sized ducks you'd

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:57.000
be willing to fight, I do actually think that's really useful.

01:02:57.000 --> 01:02:59.000
It's actually kind of interesting.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:05.000
There's a human nature, aversion to negativity stronger than a positivity.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:09.000
And this is like, how much negativity or how much resistance do you feel to this?

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:15.000
I kind of think it's a little bit, maybe not idealistic, but I think it goes in the flow

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:16.000
of humanity.

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:17.000
So I think it's a funny one.

